History of IBM: From slices of cheeses to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it was originally known as Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis for the future IBM was the fusion of four firms whose history is linked to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers," the pendules that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 presided over the Board of Supervision of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
The leader then made shadow to the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of society have so far been based.
Watson led the Kusque firm in 1952.
IBM, as his name said, began with the production of all possible machines for business and trade - from cheeses and meat trusses to the register box.
During the first four years of Watson's leadership, turnover increased to $9 million and began the expansion of the firm in all parts of the world.
Watson was so unreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of leadership his son occupied the director's chair, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first language of programming.
In the 1960s IBM people and computers helped NASA to guide the flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family - IBM System / 360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with advice and services with high added value.
The successful strategy for IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet."
Its objective is the smart use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
With regard to the IBM trade field recently developed a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps commercial people manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history on our territory as well.
She created her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also Brno's strategic outsourcing centre.
The Central and Eastern Europe Centre is located in Prague and there is also the research and development team at the global level that is responsible for the recognition of the word.
