How have travel prices changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 State travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time offered travel especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists were traveling for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962-1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovakian people) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually in Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed a letter of invitation, or the individual travel was not allowed.
The travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the West, but we had to take the tail all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The foreign exchange agreement that was the condition for travel to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, Czechoslovakian currency was not tradable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czech most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czech were buying and this habit lasts so far.
The Czech travel has since been a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czech spent 4 million days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the West has caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakian people could not travel by plane for a long time to the west that everyone wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organisations made Czech people sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a Czech trip was at that time to take with self his own food preserved, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after dozens of years of freedom to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased what has led to another important moment around 1997.
As a result of an increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have begun to prepare tours with air charters, which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s last century, Czechs had visa-free links with almost most developed countries around the world except the EU that later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
on 17 November 2008 the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully place itself in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czech for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 kroons per person for holidays abroad including ancillary expenses.
