Court validates "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analog markings by digitals is one of the more important changes that the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has led to constitutional controversy that both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have made against the presidential decree which presupposes the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been brought together.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree which details the actions to be taken to achieve the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, has been defeated for not reaching a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is a statutory award to the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero even voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversy to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all of the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
