In his intervention, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also consider it only if it is to affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the management of the State.
The substitution of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years, and this is reflected in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Ajourning change, he argued, would defer the benefits of digitalization that implies a decision in the public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
