The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the edge of the economic disaster and has put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A communiqué from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in his majority by technocrats, even though it is not clear when the new executive will take up his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the President the result of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "framework is now well traced," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to support.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a hard package of austerity required by European leaders to recover the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry up, the instability of the markets placed the performance of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years over 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian patronal Confindustria, said to the media after his meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti's success opportunities were greatly stimulated by the support of the Silvio Berlusconi PDL party, to which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," said the press Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti formed.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will probably be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that Monti's bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups, youth and women's organizations.
He will end his meeting tour Tuesday at night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief rehearsal at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should continue until the future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the widespread predictions that politicians will only give it time to implement the reforms before the elections are advanced.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it must be trained only by specialists, an index of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
