The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetic protocol of obesity of children and adolescents', which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the 20th Century National Medical Centre, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Investigation and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnical Institute (IPN).
In the investigation it is called upon to participate in the right-wing population, to present themselves to the participating sports units of IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is made to minors every Saturday from 8: 00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtemc Sportive Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity took place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sportive Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independencia Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowledge of the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on November 14 on World Diabetes Day, he mentioned that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that samedis will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size circumference), blood pressure, glucose level determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic (people associated with child obesity are being identified).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming taking of weight in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there had been an increase of 77 per cent in obesity for boys and 47 per cent for girls; with regard to overweight there was also a dramatic increase, 'said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent of Indo-American heredity, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity are translated into the inability to brush the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the full assessment of children, which allows them to be detected if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
Ila itself says that the presence of dark-colour folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of metabolic and even pre-diabetic changes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, to which each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to achieve to prevent diseases is explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarianism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, that is, the greatest consumption of sweet drinks, carbon hydrates (tamals - meat pale with maize flour wrapped in maize leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
The asphalt of UNAM would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous pavement is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even completely eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called Malthenes, which together give the pavement its viscoelastic behaviour.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behave as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes broken, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones baigned in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he said, is baigned an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through by generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would propagate better, hopefully the chemical ingenuity.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one is putting a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also baited in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion to the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it have an adequate thickness and the material made of it must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, as these affect the performance of the asphalt layer considerably.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to get out, which ramollizes all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes cassis.
In the formation trial of a cassis, he said, the first that is ruined is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Searcher System explained that vehicle load is another important factor for cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to invest and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
