For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity to be granted to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande is a banality, indicating that co-development will help to solve our "migration problem."
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electrically paying; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restoring immigration annoys growth and undermines employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants are at risk of replacing national workers, especially low-skilled workers, with downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, most of which are engaged in occupations in areas where there is a shortage of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow job supply.
A positive effect on wages
As a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has thus calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows results in an increase between 0.6% and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity provided by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization considers that in Germany, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue less expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to public budgets on average over his or her entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term of office, to search for the missing growth points "with the teeth."
The teeth in question, by being used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
