The North Stream, new Russian gas hub in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly links Western Europe to Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with glow.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government participated last Tuesday on the edges of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of North Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolitically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart of the Netherlands Mark Rutte have turned together the steering valve for the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube linking the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklembourg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the time and time completion of this huge site has a great deal of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing a little bit of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the heart of the debate, Warsaw had no hesitation to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security in its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a breach between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are highly gas-consuming, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the large smiles displayed by Gazprom leaders, present in numbers at Lubmin at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical exploit.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-gained steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"A hundred had to be abducted or destroyed by precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for North Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project leaders renounced it while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds for a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an aircraft that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of one metre in diameter, and is pushed by gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, he gives precise information about possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of the gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each), were joined.
These five companies have established a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for 20 years renewable, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the quantity of gas actually carried," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment was 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that happens before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic metres of Russian gas at every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
