Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of persons with disabilities is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disgusting?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, "the association that organizes the week for the employment of persons with disabilities."
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities there are still many obstacles before they have access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the bac and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for persons with disabilities, compared with 38% on average.
In short, all these criteria make it particularly difficult to return to employment, and are "the node of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
This is for objective brakes.
It remains the unsaid, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by IMS-Entreprendre for the City indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability," with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchair, psychiatric or intellectual disabilities."
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of workers with disabilities, as set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses," says Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20-49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100-199 employees.
